description: the official python client for prometheus one install the client two paste the following into a python interpreter three visit http localhost to view the metric from one easy to use decorator you get prometheus s rate function allows calculation of both request per second and latency over time from this data in addition if you re on linux the process metric expose cpu memory and other information about the process for free this package can be found on pypi four type of metric are offered counter gauge summary and histogram see the documentation on metric type and instrumentation best practice on how to use them counter go up and reset when the process restarts if there is a suffix of total on the metric name it will be removed when exposing the time series for counter a total suffix will be added this is for compatibility between openmetrics and the prometheus text format a openmetrics requires the total suffix there are utility to count exception raised gauge can go up and down there are utility for common use case a gauge can also take it value from a callback summary track the size and number of event there are utility for timing code the python client doesn t store or expose quantile information at this time histogram track the size and number of event in bucket this allows for aggregatable calculation of quantiles the default bucket are intended to cover a typical web rpc request from millisecond to second they can be overridden by passing bucket keyword argument to histogram there are utility for timing code info track key value information usually about a whole target enum track which of a set of state something is currently in all metric can have label allowing grouping of related time series see the best practice on naming and label taking a counter a an example label can also be passed a keyword argument metric with label are not initialized when declared because the client can t know what value the label can have it is recommended to initialize the label value by calling the label method alone exemplar can be added to counter and histogram metric exemplar can be specified by passing a dict of label value pair to be exposed a the exemplar for example with a counter and with a histogram by default counter histogram and summary export an additional series suffixed with created and a value of the unix timestamp for when the metric wa created if this information is not helpful it can be disabled by setting the environment variable prometheus disable created series true the python client automatically export metric about process cpu usage ram file descriptor and start time these all have the prefix process and are only currently available on linux the namespace and pid constructor argument allows for exporting metric about other process for example the client also automatically export some metadata about python if using jython metadata about the jvm in use is also included this information is available a label on the python info metric the value of the metric is since it is the label that carry information by default the collected process gc and platform collector metric are exported if this information is not helpful it can be disabled using the following there are several option for exporting metric metric are usually exposed over http to be read by the prometheus server the easiest way to do this is via start http server which will start a http server in a daemon thread on the given port visit http localhost to view the metric to add prometheus exposition to an existing http server see the metricshandler class which provides a basehttprequesthandler it also serf a a simple example of how to write a custom endpoint to use prometheus with twisted there is metricsresource which expose metric a a twisted resource to use prometheus with wsgi there is make wsgi app which creates a wsgi application such an application can be useful when integrating prometheus metric with wsgi apps the method start wsgi server can be used to serve the metric through the wsgi reference implementation in a new thread by default the wsgi application will respect accept encoding gzip header used by prometheus and compress the response if such a header is present this behaviour can be disabled by passing disable compression true when creating the app like this to use prometheus with asgi there is make asgi app which creates an asgi application such an application can be useful when integrating prometheus metric with asgi apps by default the wsgi application will respect accept encoding gzip header used by prometheus and compress the response if such a header is present this behaviour can be disabled by passing disable compression true when creating the app like this to use prometheus with flask we need to serve metric through a prometheus wsgi application this can be achieved using flask s application dispatching below is a working example save the snippet below in a myapp py filerun the example web application like thisvisit http localhost metric to see the metricsthe textfile collector allows machine level statistic to be exported out via the node exporter this is useful for monitoring cronjobs or for writing cronjobs to expose metric about a machine system that the node exporter doe not support or would not make sense to perform at every scrape for example anything involving subprocesses a separate registry is used a the default registry may contain other metric such a those from the process collector the pushgateway allows ephemeral and batch job to expose their metric to prometheus a separate registry is used a the default registry may contain other metric such a those from the process collector pushgateway function take a grouping key push to gateway replaces metric with the same grouping key pushadd to gateway only replaces metric with the same name and grouping key and delete from gateway deletes metric with the given job and grouping key see the pushgateway documentation for more information instance ip grouping key return a grouping key with the instance label set to the host s ip address if the push gateway you are connecting to is protected with http basic auth you can use a special handler to set the authorization header tl auth is also supported when using the push gateway with a special handler it is also possible to expose metric to system other than prometheus this allows you to take advantage of prometheus instrumentation even if you are not quite ready to fully transition to prometheus yet metric are pushed over tcp in the graphite plaintext format graphite tag are also supported sometimes it is not possible to directly instrument code a it is not in your control this requires you to proxy metric from other system to do so you need to create a custom collector for example summarymetricfamily histogrammetricfamily and infometricfamily work similarly a collector may implement a describe method which return metric in the same format a collect though you don t have to include the sample this is used to predetermine the name of time series a collectorregistry expose and thus to detect collision and duplicate registration usually custom collector do not have to implement describe if describe is not implemented and the collectorregistry wa created with auto describe true which is the case for the default registry then collect will be called at registration time instead of describe if this could cause problem either implement a proper describe or if that s not practical have describe return an empty list prometheus client library presume a threaded model where metric are shared across worker this doesn t work so well for language such a python where it s common to have process rather than thread to handle large workload to handle this the client library can be put in multiprocess mode this come with a number of limitation there s several step to getting this working deployment the prometheus multiproc dir environment variable must be set to a directory that the client library can use for metric this directory must be wiped between process gunicorn run before startup is recommended this environment variable should be set from a start up shell script and not directly from python otherwise it may not propagate to child process metric collector the application must initialize a new collectorregistry and store the multi process collector inside it is a best practice to create this registry inside the context of a request to avoid metric registering themselves to a collector used by a multiprocesscollector if a registry with metric registered is used by a multiprocesscollector duplicate metric may be exported one for multiprocess and one for the process serving the request gunicorn configuration the gunicorn configuration file need to include the following function metric tuning gauge when gauge are used in multiprocess application you must decide how to handle the metric reported by each process gauge have several mode they can run in which can be selected with the multiprocess mode parameter prepend live to the beginning of the mode to return the same result but only considering living process e g liveall livesum livemax livemin the python client support parsing the prometheus text format this is intended for advanced use case where you have server exposing prometheus metric and need to get them into some other system

description: pyotp is a python library for generating and verifying one time password it can be used to implement two factor fa or multi factor mfa authentication method in web application and in other system that require user to log in open mfa standard are defined in rfc hotp an hmac based one time password algorithm and in rfc totp time based one time password algorithm pyotp implement server side support for both of these standard client side support can be enabled by sending authentication code to user over sm or email hotp or for totp by instructing user to use google authenticator authy or another compatible app user can set up auth token in their apps easily by using their phone camera to scan otpauth qr code provided by pyotp implementers should read and follow the hotp security requirement and totp security consideration section of the relevant rfcs at minimum application implementers should follow this checklist ensure transport confidentiality by using httpsensure hotp totp secret confidentiality by storing secret in a controlled access databasedeny replay attack by rejecting one time password that have been used by the client this requires storing the most recently authenticated timestamp otp or hash of the otp in your database and rejecting the otp when a match is seen throttle rate limit brute force attack against your application s login functionalitywhen implementing a greenfield application consider supporting fido u f webauthn in addition to hotp totp u f us asymmetric cryptography to avoid using a shared secret design which strengthens your mfa solution against server side attack hardware u f also sequesters the client secret in a dedicated single purpose device which strengthens your client against client side attack and by automating scoping of credential to relying party id application origin domain name u f add protection against phishing attack one implementation of fido u f webauthn is pyotp s sister project pywarp we also recommend that implementers read the owasp authentication cheat sheet and nist sp digital authentication guideline for a high level overview of authentication best practice otps involve a shared secret stored both on the phone and the serverotps can be generated on a phone without internet connectivityotps should always be used a a second factor of authentication if your phone is lost you account is still secured with a password google authenticator and other otp client apps allow you to store multiple otp secret and provision those using a qr codea helper function is provided to generate a character base secret compatible with google authenticator and other otp apps some application want the secret key to be formatted a a hex encoded string pyotp work with the google authenticator iphone and android app a well a other otp apps like authy pyotp includes the ability to generate provisioning uris for use with the qr code scanner built into these mfa client apps this url can then be rendered a a qr code for example using http github com soldair node qrcode which can then be scanned and added to the user list of otp credential parsing these url is also supported scan the following barcode with your phone s otp app e g google authenticator now run the following and compare the output project home page github documentationpackage distribution pypi change logrfc hotp an hmac based one time passwordrfc totp time based one time password algorithmrotp original ruby otp library by mark percivalotphp php port of rotp by le lagowasp authentication cheat sheetnist sp digital authentication guidelinefor new application webauthnpywarp

description: a python library for working with data world datasets this library make it easy for data world user to pull and work with data stored on data world additionally the library provides convenient wrapper for data world apis allowing user to create and update datasets add and modify file etc and possibly implement entire apps on top of data world you can install it using pip directly from pypi optionally you can install the library including panda support if you use conda to manage your python distribution you can install from the community maintained conda forge http conda forge github io channel this library requires a data world api authentication token to work your authentication token can be obtained on data world once you enable python under integration pythonto configure the library run the following command alternatively token can be provided via the dw auth token environment variable on macos or unix machine run replacing your token below with the token obtained earlier the load dataset function facilitates maintaining copy of datasets on the local filesystem it will download a given dataset s datapackage and store it under dw cache when used subsequently load dataset will use the copy stored on disk and will work offline unless it s called with force update true or auto update true force update true will overwrite your local copy unconditionally auto update true will only overwrite your local copy if a newer version of the dataset is available on data world once loaded a dataset data and metadata can be conveniently accessed via the object returned by load dataset start by importing the datadotworld module then invoke the load dataset function to download a dataset and work with it locally for example dataset object allow access to data via three different property raw data table and dataframes each of these property is a mapping dict whose value are of type byte list and panda dataframe respectively value are lazy loaded and cached once loaded their key are the name of the file contained in the dataset for example important not all file in a dataset are tabular therefore some will be exposed via raw data only table are list of row each represented by a mapping dict of column name to their respective value for example you can also review the metadata associated with a file or the entire dataset using the describe function for example the query function allows datasets to be queried live using sql or sparql query language to query a dataset invoke the query function for example query result object allow access to the data via raw data table and dataframe property of type json list and panda dataframe respectively for example table are list of row each represented by a mapping dict of column name to their respective value for example to query using sparql invoke query using query type sparql or else it will assume the query to be a sql query just like in the dataset case you can view the metadata associated with a query result using the describe function for example the open remote file function allows you to write data to or read data from a file in a data world dataset the object that is returned from the open remote file call is similar to a file handle that would be used to write to a local file it ha a write method and content sent to that method will be written to the file remotely of course writing a text file isn t the primary use case for data world you want to write your data the return object from open remote file should be usable anywhere you could normally use a local file handle in write mode so you can use it to serialize the content of a panda dataframe to a csv file or to write a series of dict object a a json line file or to write a series of dict object a a csv and finally you can write binary data by streaming byte or bytearray object if you open the file in binary mode you can also read data from a file in a similar fashionreading from the file into common parsing library work naturally too when opened in r mode the file object act a an iterator of the line in the file reading binary file work naturally too when opened in rb mode read return the content of the file a a byte array and the file object act a an iterator of byte for a complete list of available api operation see official documentation python wrapper are implemented by the apiclient class to obtain an instance simply call api client for example the client currently implement the following function create datasetupdate datasetreplace datasetget datasetdelete datasetadd file via urlappend recordsupload filesupload filedelete filessync filesdownload datasetdownload fileget user datafetch contributing datasetsfetch liked datasetsfetch datasetsfetch contributing projectsfetch liked projectsfetch projectsget projectcreate projectupdate projectreplace projectadd linked datasetremove linked datasetdelete projectget insightget insight for projectcreate insightreplace insightupdate insightdelete insightsearch resourcescreate new tablescreate new connectionsfor a few example of what the apiclient can be used for see below the add file via url function can be used to add file to a dataset from a url this can be done by specifying file a a dictionary where the key are the desired file name and each item is an object containing url description and label for example the append record function allows you to append json data to a data stream associated with a dataset stream do not need to be created in advance stream are automatically created the first time a streamid is used in an append operation for example content of a stream will appear a part of the respective dataset a a jsonl file you can find more about those function using help client

development copy of django nested admin from source if the source is already checked out use setuptools to install to use django nested admin in your project nested admin must be added to the installed apps in your setting if you re using django grappelli you will also need to add to include nested admin url in your urlpatterns in order to use django nested admin use the following class in place of their django admin equivalent django contrib adminnested adminmodeladminnestedmodeladmininlinemodeladminnestedinlinemodeladminstackedinlinenestedstackedinlinetabularinlinenestedtabularinlinethere is also nested admin nestedgenericstackedinline and nested admin nestedgenerictabularinline which are the nesting capable version of genericstackedinline and generictabularinline in django contrib contenttypes admin django nested admin ha fairly extensive test coverage the best way to run the test is with tox which run the test against all supported django installs to run the test within a virtualenv run pytest from the repository directory the test require a selenium webdriver to be installed by default the test run with phantomjs but it is also possible to run the test with the chrome webdriver by passing selenosis driver chrome to pytest or if description: django picklefield provides an implementation of a pickled object field such field can contain any picklable object the implementation is taken and adopted from django snippet by taavi taijala which is in turn based on django snippet by oliver beattie django picklefield is available under the mit license first of all you need to have django picklefield installed for your convenience recent version should be available from pypi to use just define a field in your model and assign whatever you like a long a it s picklable to the field if you need to serialize an object with a pickledobjectfield for transmission to the browser you may need to subclass the field and override the value to string method currently pickle field are serialized a base encoded pickle which allows reliable deserialization but such a format is not convenient for parsing in the browser by overriding value to string you can choose a more convenient serialization format field now accept the boolean key word argument copy which default to true the copy is necessary for lookup to work correctly if you don t care about performing lookup on the picklefield you can set copy false to save on some memory usage this an be especially beneficial for very large object tree the full test suite can be run with tox here are the note by taavi the original author incredibly useful for storing just about anything in the database provided it is pickle able of course when there isn t a proper field for the job pickledobjectfield is database agnostic and should work with any database backend you can throw at it you can pas in any python object and it will automagically be converted behind the scene you never have to manually pickle or unpickle anything also work fine when querying support exact in and isnull lookup it should be noted however that calling queryset value will only return the encoded data not the original python object this pickledobjectfield ha a few improvement over the one in snippet this one solves the djangounicodedecodeerror problem when saving an object containing non ascii data by base encoding the pickled output stream this ensures that all stored data is ascii eliminating the problem pickledobjectfield will now optionally use zlib to compress and uncompress pickled object on the fly this can be set per field using the keyword argument compress true for most item this is probably not worth the small performance penalty but for model with larger object it can be a real space saver you can also now specify the pickle protocol per field using the protocol keyword argument the default of should always work unless you are trying to access the data from outside of the django orm worked around a rare issue when using the cpickle and performing lookup of complex data type in short cpickle would sometimes output different stream for the same object depending on how it wa referenced this of course could cause lookup for complex object to fail even when a matching object exists see the docstrings and test for more information you can now use the isnull lookup and have it function a expected a consequence of this is that by default pickledobjectfield ha null true set you can of course pas null false if you want to change that if null false is set the default for field then you wouldn t be able to store a python none value since none value aren t pickled or encoded this in turn is what make the isnull lookup possible you can now pas in an object a the default argument for the field without it being converted to a unicode string first if you pas in a callable though the field will still call it it will not try to pickle and encode it you can manually import dbsafe encode and dbsafe decode from field py if you want to encode and decode object yourself this is mostly useful for decoding value returned from calling queryset value which are still encoded string note if you are trying to store other django model in the pickledobjectfield please see the comment for a discussion on the problem associated with doing that the easy solution is to put django model into a list or tuple before assigning them to the pickledobjectfield update fixed the value to string method so that serialization should now work a expected also added deepcopy back into dbsafe encode fixing above since deepcopy had somehow managed to remove itself this mean that lookup should once again work a expected in all situation also made the field editable false by default which i swear i already did once before since it is never a good idea to have a pickledobjectfield be user editable added testing against django and none addressed a packaging issue with allowed default pickle protocol to be overriden using the picklefield default protocol setting dropped support for python added testing against django dropped support for django added official support for django thanks to joehybird dropped support for django and thanks to joehybird dropped support for python thanks to joehybidd silenced removedindjango warning warning on django thanks to canarduck restructured project directory disallowed the usage of empty string for pickledobjectfield that make save create etc raise integrityerror if null is not true and no default value wa specified like built in field do thanks to attila mihaly balazs added a check for mutable default value to pickledobjectfield added support for django and dropped support for django added a new option to prevent a copy of the object before pickling copy truedropped support for django dropped support for django dropped support for python added support for python dropped support for django dropped support for python silenced deprecation warning on django favor the built in json module thanks to simon charette python support thanks to rafal stozek allow pickling of subclass of django db model model thanks to simon charette added connection and prepared parameter to get db prep value too thanks to matthew schinckel updated link to code repository added connection and prepared parameter to get db prep lookup to get rid of deprecation warning in django fixed south support thanks aehlke github added support for south changed default to null false a is common throughout django updated copyright statement updated serialization test thanks to michael fladischer added simplified bsd licence added test for serialization added note about json serialization for browser added support for different pickle protocol version thanks to michael fladischer first public release there is a home page http github com gintas django picklefield with instruction on how to access the code repository send feedback and suggestion to gintautas miliauskas lt

description: falcon is a minimalist asgi wsgi framework for building mission critical rest apis and microservices with a focus on reliability correctness and performance at scale when it come to building http apis other framework weigh you down with ton of dependency and unnecessary abstraction falcon cut to the chase with a clean design that embrace http and the rest architectural style falcon apps work with any wsgi or asgi server and run like a champ under cpython and pypy required for asgi read the doc faq getting help reference falcon add ons and complementary packagesfalcon article talk and podcastsfalconry user for falcon user gitterfalconry dev for falcon contributor gitter falcon is rock solid and it s fast we have been using falcon a a replacement for another framework and we simply love the performance three time faster and code base size easily half of our original code i m loving falconframework super clean and simple i finally have the speed and flexibility i need falcon look great so far i hacked together a quick test for a tiny server of mine and wa faster with only minute of work i feel like i m just talking http at last with nothing in the middle falcon seems like the request of backend the source code for falcon is so good i almost prefer it to documentation it basically can t be wrong what other framework ha integrated support for try it now falcon try to do a little a possible while remaining highly effective asgi wsgi and websocket supportnative asyncio supportno reliance on magic globals for routing and state managementstable interface with an emphasis on backwards compatibilitysimple api modeling through centralized restful routinghighly optimized extensible code baseeasy access to header and body through request and response classesdry request processing via middleware component and hooksstrict adherence to rfcsidiomatic http error responsesstraightforward exception handlingsnappy testing with wsgi asgi helper and mockscpython and pypy supporthas falcon helped you make an awesome app show your support today with a one time donation or by becoming a patron supporter get cool gear an opportunity to promote their brand to python developer and prioritized support learn how to support falcon developmentthanks perfection is finally attained not when there is no longer anything to add but when there is no longer anything to take away antoine de saint exup rywe designed falcon to support the demanding need of large scale microservices and responsive app backends falcon complement more general python web framework by providing bare metal performance reliability and flexibility wherever you need it reliable we go to great length to avoid introducing breaking change and when we do they are fully documented and only introduced in the spirit of semver with a major version increment the code is rigorously tested with numerous input and we require coverage at all time falcon ha no dependency outside the standard library helping minimize your app s attack surface while avoiding transitive bug and breaking change debuggable falcon eschews magic it s easy to tell which input lead to which output unhandled exception are never encapsulated or masked potentially surprising behavior such a automatic request body parsing are well documented and disabled by default finally when it come to the framework itself we take care to keep logic path simple and understandable all this make it easier to reason about the code and to debug edge case in large scale deployment fast same hardware more request falcon turn around request significantly faster than other popular python framework like django and flask for an extra speed boost falcon compiles itself with cython when available and also work well with pypy considering a move to another programming language benchmark with falcon pypy first flexible falcon leaf a lot of decision and implementation detail to you the api developer this give you a lot of freedom to customize and tune your implementation it also help you understand your apps at a deeper level making them easier to tune debug and refactor over the long run falcon s minimalist design provides space for python community member to independently innovate on falcon add ons and complementary package falcon is used around the world by a growing number of organization including ideascronitoremchurricane electricleadpagesopenstackrackspaceshiftgigtempfil esopera softwareif you are using the falcon framework for a community or commercial project please consider adding your information to our wiki under who s using falcon a number of falcon add ons template and complementary package are available for use in your project we ve listed several of these on the falcon wiki a a starting point but you may also wish to search pypi for additional resource the falconry community on gitter is a great place to ask question and share your idea you can find u in falconry user we also have a falconry dev room for discussing the design and development of the framework itself per our code of conduct we expect everyone who participates in community discussion to act professionally and lead by example in encouraging constructive discussion each individual in the community is responsible for creating a positive constructive and productive culture pypy is the fastest way to run your falcon app pypy is supported a of pypy v or to install the latest beta or release candidate if any falcon also fully support cpython the latest stable version of falcon can be installed directly from pypi or to install the latest beta or release candidate if any in order to provide an extra speed boost falcon can compile itself with cython wheel containing pre compiled binary are available from pypi for several common platform however if a wheel for your platform of choice is not available you can install the source distribution the installation process will automatically try to cythonize falcon for your environment falling back to a normal pure python install if any issue are encountered during the cythonization step if you want to verify that cython is being invoked simply pas the verbose flag v to pip in order to echo the compilation command the cythonization step is only active when using the cpython python implementation so installing using pypy will skip it if you want to skip cython compilation step and install the pure python version directly you can set the environment variable falcon disable cython to a non empty value before description: this package is the canonical python binding for the mujoco physic engine these binding are developed and maintained by deepmind and is kept up to date with the latest development in mujoco itself the mujoco package provides direct access to raw mujoco c api function structs constant and enumeration structs are provided a python class with pythonic initialization and deletion semantics it is not the aim of this package to provide fully fledged scene environment game authoring api a there are already a number of existing package that do this well however this package doe provide a number of lower level component outside of mujoco itself that are likely to be useful to most user who access mujoco through python for example the egl glfw and osmesa subpackages contain utility for setting up opengl rendering context the recommended way to install this package is via pypi a copy of the mujoco library is provided a part of the package and doe not need to be downloaded or installed separately important building from source is only necessary if you are modifying the python binding or are trying to run on exceptionally old linux system if that s not the case then we recommend installing the prebuilt binary from pypi make sure you have cmake and a c compiler installed download the latest binary release from github on macos the download corresponds to a dmg file from which you can drag mujoco app into your application folder clone the entire mujoco repository from github and cd into the python directory create a virtual environment generate a source distribution tarball with the make sdist sh script the make sdist sh script generates additional c header file that are needed to build the binding and also pull in required file from elsewhere in the case is one possible application of the module is writing secure administration tool another application is in writing daemon and server client and server can encrypt the data being exchanged and mutually authenticate themselves daemon can encrypt private data for added security python also provides a pleasant framework for prototyping and experimentation with cryptographic algorithm thanks to it arbitrary length integer public key algorithm are easily implemented a of pycrypto pycrypto provides an easy to use random number generator a stronger version of python s standard random module is also provided caveat for the random number generator to work correctly you must call random atfork in both the parent and child process after using o fork pycrypto is written and tested using python version through python is not supported the module are packaged using the distutils so you can simply run python setup py build to build the package and python setup py install to install it if the description: flask login provides user session management for flask it handle the common task of logging in logging out and remembering your user session over extended period of time flask login is not bound to any particular database system or permission model the only requirement is that your user object implement a few method and that you provide a callback to the extension capable of loading user from their id install the extension with pip once installed the flask login is easy to use let s walk through setting up a basic application also please note that this is a very basic guide we will be taking shortcut here that you should never take in a real application to begin we ll set up a flask app flask login work via a login manager to kick thing off we ll set up the login manager by instantiating it and telling it about our flask app to keep thing simple we re going to use a dictionary to represent a database of user in a real application this would be an actual persistence layer however it s important to point out this is a feature of flask login it doesn t care how your data is stored so long a you tell it how to retrieve it we also need to tell flask login how to load a user from a flask request and from it session to do this we need to define our user object a user loader callback and a request loader callback now we re ready to define our view we can start with a login view which will populate the session with authentication bit after that we can define a view that requires authentication finally we can define a view to clear the session and log user out we now have a basic working application that make use of session based authentication to round thing off we should provide a callback for login failure documentation for flask login is available on readthedocs for complete understanding of available configuration please refer to the source code we welcome contribution if you would like to hack on flask login please follow these step please give u adequate time to review your submission thanks

description: sqlalchemy json provides mutation tracked json type to sqlalchemy mutablejson is a straightforward implementation for keeping track of top level change to json object nestedmutablejson is an extension of this which track change even when these happen in nested object or array python dicts and list this is essentially the sqlalchemy mutable json recipe we define a simple author model which list the author s name and a property handle for various social medium handle used the example below load one of the existing author and retrieves the mapping of social medium handle the error in the twitter handle is then corrected and committed the change is detected by sqlalchemy and the appropriate update statement is generated the example below defines a simple model for article one of the property on this model is a mutable json structure called reference which includes a count of link that the article contains grouped by domain with this in place an existing article is loaded and it current reference inspected following that the count for one of these is increased by ten and the session is committed had the article model used mutablejson like in the previous example this code would have failed this is because the top level dictionary is never altered directly the nested mutable ensures the change happening at the lower level bubble up to the outermost container by default sqlalchemy json us the json column type provided by sqlalchemy specifically sqlalchemy type json if you wish to use another type e g postgresql s jsonb your database doe not natively support json e g version of sqlite before or you wish to serialize to a format other than json you ll need to provide a different backing type this is done by using the utility function mutable json type this type creator function accepts two parameter dbtype control the database type used this can be an existing type provided by sqlalchemy or sqlalchemy utils or an augmented type to provide serialization to any other format nested control whether the created type is made mutable based on mutabledict or nestedmutable default to false for mutabledict six to support both python and fix a lingering python compatibility issue cmp parameter for trackedlist sort add pickling and unpickling support http github com edelooff sqlalchemy json pull add tracking for dictionary in place update http github com switch json base type to sqlalchemy type json from deprecated json type provided by sqlalchemy utils fix a bug where assigning none to the column resulted in an error http github com edelooff sqlalchemy json issue fix a typo in the readme found after uploading to pypi now us jsontype provided by sqlalchemy utils to handle backend storage backwards incompatible changed class name jsonobject to mutablejson and nestedjsonobject to nestedmutablejsonoutermost container for nestedmutablejson can now be an array python list initial version this initially carried a version number but ha never been released on pypi

is used while wrapt objectproxy just forward the method call to the target object in other word you use lazy object proxy when you only have the object way later and you use wrapt objectproxy when you want to override few method by subclassing and forward everything else to the target object example http python lazy object proxy readthedocs io to run all the test run this project is based on some code from wrapt a you can see in the git history cleaned up use of cpickle contributed by sandro tosi in cleaned up more dead python code added python wheel dropped support for python removed most of the python support code and fixed python requires to require at least python note that ha been yanked because it could not install on python installing lazy object proxy on python should automatically fall back to the release now switched ci to github action this ha a couple consequence support for python is dropped you can still install it there but it s not tested anymore and python specific handling will be removed at some point linux wheel are now provided in musllinux and manylinux variant fixed index to fallback to int if the wrapped object doesn t have an index method this prevents situation where code using a proxy would otherwise likely just call int had the object not have an index method added support for async special method aiter anext await aenter aexit these are used in the async for await and async with statement note that await return a wrapper that try to emulate the crazy stuff going on in the ceval loop so there will be a small performance overhead added the resolved property you can use it to check if the factory ha been called added python wheel removed python window wheel not supported on newest image with python added arm wheel manylinux added support for fspath dropped support for python added binary wheel for python fixed license metadata included a pyproject toml to allow user install the sdist with old python setuptools a the setuptools scm dep will be fetched by pip instead of setuptools fix fixed wheel being built with coverage cflags no more issue about bogus cext gcda file removed useless c file from wheel changed setup py to use setuptools scm fixed mod for the slot backend contributed by ran benita in dropped support for python and contributed by hugovk in fix broken release sdist had a broken manifest in speed up arithmetic operation involving cext proxy subclass added manylinux wheel minor cleanup in readme fix a memory leak the wrapped object would get bogus reference contributed by astrum kuo in don t instantiate the object when repr is called this aid with debugging allows one to see exactly in what state the proxy is added support for pickling the pickled value is going to be the wrapped object without any proxy container fixed a memory management issue in the c extension reference cycle weren t garbage collected due to improper handling in the c extension contributed by alvin chow in first release on pypi

description: pidfile class featuring stale detectionpidfile locking fcntl chmod default is o chowncustom exceptionspidfile can be used a a context manager logging to file is also possible when using pidfile with a daemon context manager e g python daemon this requires some care in handling the open file when the daemon start to avoid closing them which cause problem with the logging in particular the open handler should be preserved this assumes a logging conf file ha been created see e g basic tutorial for logging pidfile can also be used a a decorator in default mode pidfile will try to acquire a file lock before anything else this mean that normally you get a pidfilealreadylockederror instead of the pidfilealreadyrunningerror when running a program twice if you just want to know if a program is already running it easiest to catch just pidfileerror since it will capture all possible pidfile exception change in version and going forward pid is now friendly with daemon context manager such a python daemon where the pidfile context manager is passed a a parameter the new corrected behaviour will ensure the process environment is determined at the time of acquiring checking the lock prior behaviour would determine the process environment when instancing the class which may result in incorrect determination of the pid in the case of a process forking after instancing pidfile cleanup of pidfile on termination is done using atexit module the default sigterm handler doesn t cleanly exit and therefore the atexit registered function will not execute a custom handler which trigger the atexit registered function for cleanup will override the default sigterm handler if a prior signal handler ha been configured then it will not be overridden

description: stop plotting your data annotate your data and let it visualize itself holoviews is an open source python library designed to make data analysis and visualization seamless and simple with holoviews you can usually express what you want to do in very few line of code letting you focus on what you are trying to explore and convey not on the process of plotting check out the holoviews web site for extensive example and documentation holoviews work with python on linux window or mac and work seamlessly with jupyter notebook and jupyterlab the recommended way to install holoviews is using the conda command provided by anaconda or miniconda this command will install the typical package most useful with holoviews though holoviews itself depends only on numpy panda and param additional installation and configuration option are described in the user guide you can also clone holoviews directly from github and install it with once you ve installed holoviews you can get a copy of all the example shown on this website now you can launch jupyter notebook or jupyterlab to explore them if you are working with a jupyterlab version you will also need the pyviz jupyterlab extension for more detail on setup and configuration see our website for general discussion we have a gitter channel if you find any bug or have any feature suggestion please file a github issue or submit a pull request

description: panel provides tool for easily composing widget plot table and other viewable object and control into custom analysis tool apps and dashboard panel work with visualization from altair bokeh holoviews matplotlib plotly pydeck pyvista and many other python plotting library making them instantly viewable either individually or when combined with interactive widget that control them panel work equally well in jupyter notebook for creating quick data exploration tool or a standalone deployed apps and dashboard and allows you to easily switch between those context a needed panel make it simple to make panel object are reactive immediately updating to reflect change to their state which make it simple to compose viewable object and link them into simple one off apps to do a specific exploratory task the same object can then be reused in more complex combination to build more ambitious apps while always sharing the same code that work well on it own panel can also be used with the separate param project to create interactively configurable object with or without associated visualization in a fully declarative way with this approach you declare your configurable object using the pure python zero dependency param library annotating your code with parameter range documentation and dependency between parameter and your code using this information you can make all of your domain specific code be optionally configurable in a gui with optional visual display and debugging information if you like all with just a few line of declaration with this approach you don t ever have to commit to whether your code will be used in a notebook in a gui app or completely behind the scene in batch processing or report the same code can support all of these case equally well once you declare the associated parameter and constraint this approach let you completely separate your domain specific code from anything to do with web browser gui toolkits or other volatile technology that would otherwise make your hard work become obsolete a they change over time panel can be used in a wide range of development environment you can edit your panel code a a py file in any text editor marking the object you want to render a servable then launch a server with to open a browser tab showing your app or dashboard and backed by a live python process the autoreload flag ensures that the app reloads whenever you make a change to the python source in the classic jupyter notebook environment and jupyterlab first make sure to load the pn extension panel object will then render themselves if they are the last item in a notebook cell for version of jupyterlab the necessary extension is automatically bundled in the pyviz comms package which must be however note that for version of jupyterlab you must also manually install the jupyterlab extension with in the google colaboratory notebook first make sure to load the pn extension panel object will then render themselves if they are the last item in a notebook cell please note that in colab rendering for each notebook cell is isolated which mean that every cell must reload the panel extension code separately this will result in somewhat slower and larger notebook than with other notebook technology visual studio code vscode version and later support ipywidgets and panel object can be used a ipywidgets since panel thanks to jupyter bokeh which mean that you can now use panel component interactively in vscode ensure you install jupyter bokeh with pip install jupyter bokeh or conda install c bokeh jupyter bokeh and then enable the extension with pn extension in other notebook environment that support rendering ipywidgets interactively such a nteract you can use the same underlying ipywidgets support a for vscode install jupyter bokeh and then use pn extension comms ipywidgets if your development environment offer embedded python process but doe not support ipywidgets or jupyter comms communication channel you will notice that some or all interactive functionality is missing some widget that operate only in javascript will work fine but others require communication channel between javascript and python in such case you can either request ipywidgets or panel support from the editor or environment or else use the editor server approach above the panel project is grateful for the sponsorship by the organization and company below

description: installation configuration resource displayed contributing jupyter resource usage is an extension for jupyter notebook and jupyterlab that display an indication of how much resource your current notebook server and it child kernel terminal etc are using this is displayed in the main toolbar in the notebook itself refreshing every s you can currently install this package from pypi or with conda if your notebook version is you need to enable the extension manually jupyter resource usage can display a memory limit but not enforce it you can set this in several way the limit need to be set a an integer in byte the background of the resource display can be changed to red when the user is near a memory limit the threshold for this warning can be configured a a fraction of the memory limit if you want to flash the warning to the user when they are within of the memory limit you can set the parameter resourceusedisplay mem warning threshold jupyter resource usage can also track cpu usage and report a cpu percent value a part of the api metric v response you can set the cpu limit in several way the limit corresponds to the number of cpu the user ha access to but doe not enforce it additionally you can set the track cpu percent trait to enable cpu usage tracking disabled by default a a command line argument there is a known bug with prometheus metric which cause lag pause in the ui to workaround this you can disable prometheus metric reporting using currently the server extension only report memory usage just r and cpu usage other metric will be added in the future a needed the notebook extension currently doesn t show cpu usage only memory usage if you would like to contribute to the project please read the contributing md the contributing md file explains how to set up a development installation and how to run the test suite

description: google cloud pub sub is a fully managed real time messaging service that allows you to send and receive message between independent application you can leverage cloud pub sub s flexibility to decouple system and component hosted on google cloud platform or elsewhere on the internet by building on the same technology google us cloud pub sub is designed to provide at least once delivery at low latency with on demand scalability to million message per second and beyond publisher application can send message to a topic and other application can subscribe to that topic to receive the message by decoupling sender and receiver google cloud pub sub allows developer to communicate between independently written application product documentationclient library documentationin order to use this library you first need to go through the following step select or create a cloud platform project enable billing for your project enable the google cloud pub sub api setup authentication install this library in a virtualenv using pip virtualenv is a tool to create isolated python environment the basic problem it address is one of dependency and version and indirectly permission with virtualenv it s possible to install this library without needing system install permission and without clashing with the installed system dependency python python the last version of this library compatible with python is google cloud pubsub to publish data to cloud pub sub you must create a topic and then publish message to itto learn more consult the publishing documentation to subscribe to data in cloud pub sub you create a subscription based on the topic and subscribe to that passing a callback function the future returned by the call to subscriber subscribe can be used to block the current thread until a given condition obtains it is also possible to pull message in a synchronous blocking fashion to learn more about subscribing consult the subscriber documentation it is possible to specify the authentication method to use with the pub sub client this can be done by providing an explicit credential instance support for various authentication method is available from the google auth library for example to use json web token provide a google auth jwt credential instance this library follows semantic versioning it is currently in major version one y z which mean that the public api should be considered stable contribution to this library are always welcome and highly encouraged see the contributing doc for more information on how to get started google description: cloud firestore api is a fully managed nosql document database for mobile web and server development from firebase and google cloud platform it s backed by a multi region replicated database that ensures once data is committed it s durable even in the face of unexpected disaster not only that but despite being a distributed database it s also strongly consistent and offer seamless integration with other firebase and google cloud platform product including google cloud function client library documentationproduct documentationin order to use this library you first need to go through the following step select or create a cloud platform project enable billing for your project enable the cloud firestore api setup authentication install this library in a virtualenv using pip virtualenv is a tool to create isolated python environment the basic problem it address is one of dependency and version and indirectly permission with virtualenv it s possible to install this library without needing system install permission and without clashing with the installed system dependency code sample and snippet live in the sample folder our client library are compatible with all current active and maintenance version of python python python if you are using an end of life version of python we recommend that you update a soon a possible to an actively supported version read the client library documentation for cloud firestore api to see other available method on the client read the cloud firestore api product documentation to learn more about the product and see how to guide view this readme to see the full list of cloud apis that we cover

description: environs is a python library for parsing environment variable it allows you to store configuration separate from your code a per the twelve factor app methodology with some environment variable set parse them with environs the following are all type casting method of env call env read env before parsing variable by default env read env will look for a env file in current directory and if no env exists in the cwd recurse upwards until a env file is found you can also read a specific file by default a validation error is raised immediately upon calling a parser method for an invalid environment variable to defer validation and raise an exception with the combined error message for all invalid variable pas eager false to env call env seal after all variable have been parsed env seal validates all parsed variable and prevents further parsing calling a parser method will raise an error load the configuration after you initialize your app for local development use a env file to override the default configuration note because environs depends on python dotenv the flask cli will automatically read env and flaskenv file environs includes a number of helper for parsing connection url to install environs with django support use env dj db url env dj cache url and env dj email url to parse the database url cache url and email url environment variable respectively for more detail on url pattern see the following project that environs is using for converting url basic example for local development use a env file to override the default configuration for a more complete example see django example py in the example directory see the factor app section on configuration while o environ is enough for simple use case a typical application will need a way to manipulate and validate raw environment variable environs abstract common task for handling environment variable environs will help youthere are many great python library for parsing environment variable in fact most of the credit for environs public api go to the author of envparse and django environ environs aim to meet three additional goal see this github issue which detail specific difference with envparse mit licensed see the license file for more detail

description: warning this project is currently in beta please open an issue if you would like to report a bug or documentation issue request a feature or have a question the cloud sql python connector is a cloud sql connector designed for use with the python language using a cloud sql connector provides the following benefit the cloud sql python connector is a package to be used alongside a database driver currently supported driver are you can install this library with pip install specifying the driver based on your database dialect there are two different database driver that are supported for the postgres dialect this package provides several function for authorizing and encrypting connection these function are used with your database driver to connect to your cloud sql instance the instance connection name for your cloud sql instance is always in the format project region instance this package requires the following to successfully make cloud sql connection this library us the application default credential adc strategy for resolving credential please see these instruction for how to set your adc google cloud application v local development iam user v service account credential or consult the google auth package to explicitly set a specific source for the credential see configuring the connector below to connect to cloud sql using the connector inititalize a connector object and call it s connect method with the proper input parameter the connector itself creates connection object by calling it connect method but doe not manage database connection pooling for this reason it is recommended to use the connector alongside a library that can create connection pool such a sqlalchemy this will allow for connection to remain open and be reused reducing connection overhead and the number of connection needed in the connector s connect method below input your connection string a the first positional argument and the name of the database driver for the second positional argument insert the rest of your connection keyword argument like user password and database you can also set the optional timeout or ip type keyword argument to use this connector with sqlalchemy use the creator argument for sqlalchemy create engine the returned connection pool engine can then be used to query and modify the database to close the connector object s background resource call it s close method a follows note for more example of using sqlalchemy to manage connection pooling with the connector please see cloud sql sqlalchemy sample note for sql server user if your sql server instance requires ssl you need to download the ca certificate for your instance and include cafile path to downloaded certificate and validate host false this is a workaround for a known issue if you need to customize something about the connector or want to specify default for each connection to make you can initialize a connector object a follows the connector object can also be used a a context manager in order to automatically close and cleanup resource removing the need for explicit call to connector close connector a a context manager the cloud sql connector for python can be used to connect to cloud sql instance using both public and private ip address to specify which ip address to use to connect set the ip type keyword argument possible value are iptypes public and iptypes private example note if specifying private ip your application must already be in the same vpc network a your cloud sql instance connection using automatic iam database authentication are supported when using the postgres driver this feature is unsupported for other driver if automatic iam authentication is not supported for your driver you can use manual iam database authentication to connect first make sure to configure your cloud sql instance to allow iam authentication and add an iam database user now you can connect using user or service account credential instead of a password in the call to connect set the enable iam auth keyword argument to true and user to the email address associated with your iam user example active directory authentication for sql server instance is currently only supported on window first make sure to follow these step to set up a managed ad domain and join your cloud sql instance to the domain see here for more info on cloud sql active directory integration once you have followed the step linked above you can run the following code to return a connection object or if using private ip the python connector can be used alongside popular python web framework such a flask fastapi etc to integrate cloud sql database within your web application flask sqlalchemy is an extension for flask that add support for sqlalchemy to your application it aim to simplify using sqlalchemy with flask by providing useful default and extra helper that make it easier to accomplish common task you can configure flask sqlalchemy to connect to a cloud sql database from your web application through the following for more detail on how to use flask sqlalchemy check out the flask sqlalchemy quickstartsfastapi is a modern fast high performance web framework for building apis with python based on standard python type hint you can configure fastapi to connect to a cloud sql database from your web application using sqlalchemy orm through the following to learn more about integrating a database into your fastapi application follow along the fastapi sql database guide the cloud sql connector is compatible with asyncio to improve the speed and efficiency of database connection through concurrency you can use all non asyncio driver through the connector connect async function in addition to the following asyncio database driver the cloud sql connector ha a helper create async connector function that is recommended for asyncio database connection it return a connector object that us the current thread s running event loop this is different than connector which by default initializes a new event loop in a background thread the create async connector allows all the same input argument a the connector object once a connector object is returned by create async connector you can call it connect async method just a you would the connect method for more detail on interacting with an asyncpg connection please visit the official documentation an alternative to using the create async connector function is initializing a connector a an async context manager removing the need for explicit call to connector close async to cleanup resource note this alternative requires that the running event loop be passed in a the loop argument to connector this project us semantic versioning and us the following lifecycle regarding support for a major version active active version get all new feature and security fix that wouldn t otherwise introduce a breaking change new major version are guaranteed to be active for a minimum of year deprecated deprecated version continue to receive security and critical bug fix but do not receive new feature deprecated version will be publicly supported for year unsupported any major version that ha been deprecated for year is considered publicly unsupported we test and support at a minimum every active version until it s end of life date change in supported python version will be considered a minor change and will be listed in the release note this project aim for a minimum monthly release cadence if no new feature or fix have been added a new patch version with the latest dependency is released we welcome outside contribution please see our contributing guide for detail on how best to contribute

description: asynchronous parallel ssh client library run ssh command over many hundred hundred of thousand number of server asynchronously and with minimal system load on the client host native code based client with extremely high performance making use of c library an update to pip may be needed to be able to install binary wheel see documentation on read the doc for more complete example run uname on two host in parallel single host client with similar api can be used if parallel functionality is not needed contentsinstallationusage examplesingle host clientquestions and discussionnative clientsnative code client featureswhy this librarywaiting for completion and exit codesbuilt in host output loggerscpsftpgithub discussion can be used to discus ask question and share idea regarding the use of parallel ssh the default client in parallel ssh is a native client based on ssh python libssh c library which offer much greater performance and reduced overhead compared to other python ssh library see this post for a performance comparison of different python ssh library alternative client based on ssh python libssh are also available under pssh client ssh see client documentation for a feature comparison of the available client in the library parallel ssh make use of client and an event loop solely based on c library providing native code level of performance and stability with an easy to use python api highest performance and least overhead of any python ssh librarythread safe make use of native thread for cpu bound call like authenticationnatively asynchronous utilising c library implementing the ssh protocolsignificantly reduced overhead in cpu and memory usagebecause other option are either immature unstable lacking in performance or all of the aforementioned certain other self proclaimed leading python ssh library leave a lot to be desired from a performance and stability point of view a well a suffering from a lack of maintenance with hundred of open issue unresolved pull request and inherent design flaw the ssh library parallel ssh us are on the other hand long standing mature c library in libssh and libssh that have been in production use for decade and are part of some of the most widely distributed software available today git itself openssh curl and many others these low level library are far better placed to provide the maturity stability and performance needed from an ssh client for production use parallel ssh provides easy to use ssh client that hide the complexity while offering stability and native code level of performance and a well a the ability to scale to hundred or more concurrent host see alternative for a more complete comparison of alternative ssh library a well a performance comparison mentioned previously the client s join function can be used to wait for all command in output to finish after join return command have finished and all output can be read without blocking once either standard output is iterated on to completion or client join is called exit code become available in host output iteration end only when remote command ha completed though it may be interrupted and resumed at any point see join and output timeouts documentation hostoutput exit code is a dynamic property and will return none when exit code is not ready meaning command ha not finished or unavailable due to error once all output ha been gathered exit code become available even without calling join a per previous example similarly exit code are available after client join without reading output there is also a built in host logger that can be enabled to log output from remote host for both stdout and stderr the helper function pssh utils enable host logger will enable host logging to stdout to log output without having to iterate over output generator the consume output flag must be enabled for example scp is supported native client only and provides the best performance for file copying unlike with the sftp functionality remote file that already exist are not overwritten and an exception is raised instead note that enabling recursion with scp requires server sftp support for creating remote directory to copy a local file to remote host in parallel with scp see sftp and scp documentation for more example sftp is supported in the native client to copy a local file to remote host in parallel there is similar capability to copy remote file to local one with configurable file name via the copy remote file function in addition per host configurable file name functionality is provided for both sftp and scp see documentation directory recursion is supported in both case via the recurse parameter default to off see sftp and scp documentation for more example

description: scholarly is a module that allows you to retrieve author and publication information from google scholar in a friendly pythonic way without having to solve captchas scholarly can be installed either with conda or with pip to install using conda simply runalternatively use pip to install the latest release from pypi or pip to install from github we are constantly developing new feature please update your local package regularly scholarly follows semantic versioning this mean your code that us an earlier version of scholarly is guaranteed to work with newer version tor scholarly come with a handful of apis to set up proxy to circumvent anti bot measure tor method are deprecated since v and are not actively tested or supported if you wish to use tor install scholarly using the tor tag asif you use zsh which is now the default in latest macos you should type this asnote tor option is unavailable with conda installation to check if your installation is succesful run the test by executing the test module py file a orcheck the documentation for a complete api reference and a quickstart guide important making certain type of query such a scholarly citedby or scholarly search pub will lead to google scholar blocking your request and may eventually block your ip address you must use proxy service to avoid this situation see the using proxy section in the documentation for more detail here s a short example scholarly also ha apis that work with several premium paid proxy service scholarly is smart enough to know which query need proxy and which do not it is therefore recommended to always set up a proxy in the beginning of your application the developer use scraperapi to run the test in github action the developer of scholarly are not affiliated with any of the proxy service and do not profit from them if your favorite service is not supported please submit an issue or even better follow it up with a pull request we welcome contribution from you please create an issue fork this repository and submit a pull request read the contributing document for more information if you have used this codebase in a scientific publication please cite this software a following the original code that this project wa forked from wa released by luciano bello under a wtfpl license in keeping with this mentality all code is released under the unlicense

description: by design asyncio doe not allow it event loop to be nested this present a practical problem when in an environment where the event loop is already running it s impossible to run task and wait for the result trying to do so will give the error runtimeerror this event loop is already running the issue pop up in various environment such a web server gui application and in jupyter notebook this module patch asyncio to allow nested use of asyncio run and loop run until complete python or higher is required optionally the specific loop that need patching can be given a argument to apply otherwise the current event loop is used an event loop can be patched whether it is already running or not only event loop from asyncio can be patched loop from other project such a uvloop or quamash generally can t be patched
